  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Attached Object Pronouns",
      "titleArabic": "الضمائر المتصلة (المفعول به)",
      "content": [
        "Object pronouns attach directly to verbs to indicate the receiver of the action. These pronouns are in the accusative case (منصوب) since they function as the object.",
        "The attached pronoun changes form based on what precedes it. When attached to a verb ending in a vowel, the pronoun joins smoothly."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "ـنِي (me) - first person singular",
        "ـهُ (him/it) - third person masculine singular",
        "ـهَا (her/it) - third person feminine singular",
        "ـكَ (you, m.) - second person masculine singular",
        "ـكِ (you, f.) - second person feminine singular"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "رَآنِي", "english": "He saw me" },
        { "arabic": "رَأَيْتُهُ", "english": "I saw him" },
        { "arabic": "سَاعَدَهَا", "english": "He helped her" },
        { "arabic": "سَأَلَتْنِي", "english": "She asked me" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Verb-Pronoun Combinations",
      "titleArabic": "اتصال الضمائر بالأفعال",
      "content": [
        "When combining verbs with object pronouns, pay attention to the voweling changes that occur for smooth pronunciation."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "The verb's final vowel may change when a pronoun is attached",
        "First person pronoun ـنِي always has kasrah before ya",
        "Third person pronouns ـهُ/ـهَا have dammah/fathah respectively"
      ]
    }
  ],
